{"id":"1611.02131","submitter":"Jesper Hansen JSH","authors":"Jesper Schmidt Hansen","title":"Multiscale response of ionic systems to a spatially varying electric\n  field","comments":null,"journal-ref":"SciPost Phys. 2, 017 (2017)","doi":"10.21468/SciPostPhys.2.3.017","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mes-hall physics.chem-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this paper the response of ionic systems subjected to a spatially varying\nelectric field is studied. Following the Nernst-Planck equation, two forces\ndriving the mass flux are present, namely, the concentration gradient and the\nelectric potential gradient. The mass flux due to the concentration gradient is\nmodelled through Fick's law, and a new constitutive relation for the mass flux\ndue to the potential gradient is proposed. In the regime of low screening the\nresponse function due to the potential gradient is closely related to the ionic\nconductivity. In the large screening regime, on the other hand, the response\nfunction is governed by the charge-charge structure. Molecular dynamics\nsimulations are conducted and the two wave vector dependent response functions\nare evaluated for models of a molten salt and an ionic liquid. In the low\nscreening regime the response functions show same wave vector dependency,\nindicating that it is the same underlying physical processes that govern the\nresponse. In the screening regime the wave vector dependency is very different\nand, thus, the overall response is determined by different processes. This is\nin agreement with the observed failure of the Nernst-Einstein relation.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 7 Nov 2016 15:51:19 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 9 Nov 2016 13:24:05 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 15 Feb 2017 17:35:13 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-04-20"}
